    <!-- Add insight / key takeaway directly related to activity / learner experience -->

    <insight>
        <p>
            Logarithmic equations are powerful tools that can help us understand and solve a wide range of real-life problems, from population growth to sound intensity. By applying logarithmic properties and calculations, we can make sense of complex phenomena and make informed decisions based on data.
        </p>
    </insight> 

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
         <p>
            A bacterium population doubles every 3 hours. If the initial population is 100, how many bacteria will there be after 24 hours? Use logarithms to solve this problem.
         </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Let P(t) be the population at time t hours. We can express the population growth as:
            </p>
            <p>
               <m>P(t) = P_0 * 2^(t/3)</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Where P_0 is the initial population (100) and t is the time in hours. We want to find P(24):
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>P(24) = 100 * 2^(24/3) = 100 * 2^8 = 100 * 256 = 25600</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, after 24 hours, there will be 25,600 bacteria.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The intensity of a sound is measured in decibels (dB) and is given by the formula:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>I = 10 * log_{10}(P/P_0)</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Where I is the intensity in decibels, P is the power of the sound, and P_0 is the reference power (the threshold of hearing). If a sound has a power of 1 watt and the reference power is 10^-12 watts, what is the intensity of the sound in decibels?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Substituting the values into the formula:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>I = 10 * log_{10}(1 / 10^{-12}) = 10 * log_{10}(10^{12}) = 10 * 12 = 120</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, the intensity of the sound is 120 decibels.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A radioactive substance decays at a rate proportional to its current amount. If the half-life of the substance is 5 years, how long will it take for a sample of 100 grams to decay to 25 grams? Use logarithms to solve this problem.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Let P(t) be the amount of the substance at time t years. The decay can be modeled as:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>P(t) = P_0 * (1/2)^(t/5)</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Where P_0 is the initial amount (100 grams) and t is the time in years. We want to find t when P(t) = 25:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>25 = 100 * (1/2)^(t/5)</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Dividing both sides by 100:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>0.25 = (1/2)^(t/5)</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Taking the logarithm base 2 of both sides:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>log_2(0.25) = t/5</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Since log_2(0.25) = log_2(1/4) = -2:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>-2 = t/5</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Multiplying both sides by 5:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>t = -10</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Since time cannot be negative, we take the absolute value:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>t = 10</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, it will take 10 years for the sample to decay to 25 grams.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

